<lb corresp="#b4"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>ya</supplied>thaiva</w><pc>•</pc><w>kṣātre</w><w>o<supplied>rotstse</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/>
<lb corresp="#b5"/><gap reason="lost"/><w><supplied>dha</supplied>r<supplied>ma</supplied>cārī</w><pc>•</pc><w>mā</w><w>y<supplied>olo</supplied></w><gap reason="lost"/></p>
         </div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p><choice corresp="#a1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB]: (give up in the middle, having reached the other shore) of existence</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT]: <hi>yugavarga</hi></seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB]: from victory one carries off enmity [SKT]: the defeated dwells in sorrow</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB]: having given up both victory (and defeat)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#a5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT]: united (in close connection with enmity) [TB]: (united in close connection with) enmity</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b1"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB]: longing for his own happiness</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b2"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[TB]: one should practise (the law well) [SKT]: not (should) one (do what is bad conduct)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b3"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT]: (in this world) and in the next [TB]: in this world (and in the next)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b4"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT]: like (a large umbrella in the rainy season) [TB]: (like) a large umbrella (in the rainy season)</seg></seg></choice><choice corresp="#b5"><seg><seg type="prim_transl">[SKT]: he who practises the law (does not go to a bad existence) [TB]: (he who practises the law does not go) to a bad (existence)</seg></seg></choice></p>
         </div>
         <div type="comments">
            <p><note type="parallels"><bibl><title corresp="ref:bernhard1965"/><citedRange>393</citedRange></bibl>; <bibl><title corresp="ref:hahn2007"/><citedRange>116-117</citedRange></bibl></note><note corresp="#a1" type="philcomment">Uv.29.57b <hi>madhye muñca bhavasya pāragaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment">Uv.29.57end <hi>yugavargaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#a2" type="philcomment"><hi>6</hi>: with a vertical stroke between the <distinct type="ms_text">_ś</distinct> and the <hi>u</hi>, with a horizontal one crossing. Perhaps it is to be read <hi>7</hi>, i.e. 6 + 1. Otherwise, in this version the yugavarga may have contained 56, not 57 pādas, which would also be possible.</note><note corresp="#a3" type="philcomment">Uv.30.1a-b <hi>jayād vairaṃ prasavate duḥkhaṃ śete parājitaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">Uv.30.1d <hi>hitvā jayaparājayau</hi></note><note corresp="#a4" type="philcomment">: of the first akṣara the rest of an arc can be seen, which could be of a long <hi>ī</hi>.</note><note corresp="#a5" type="philcomment">Uv.30.2c <hi>vairasaṃsargasaṃsakto</hi></note><note corresp="#b1" type="philcomment">Uv.30.4c <hi>ātmanaḥ sukham eṣānaḥ</hi></note><note corresp="#b2" type="philcomment">Uv.30.5a-b <hi>dharmaṃ caret sucaritaṃ nainaṃ duścaritaṃ caret</hi></note><note corresp="#b3" type="philcomment">Uv.30.5d <hi>nainaṃ duścaritaṃ caret</hi></note><note corresp="#b4" type="philcomment">Uv.30.6b <hi>chatraṃ mahad varṣakāle yathaiva</hi></note><note corresp="#b5" type="philcomment">Uv.30.6d <hi>na durgatiṃ gacchati dharmacārī</hi></note></p>
         </div>
